flowRoot.flowPara: Question: How large is the muon-induced background at LNGS?
The cosmic muon-induced background for the LEGEND-1000 Alternative Site at LNGS
Authors: Moritz Neuberger (1), Luigi Pertoldi (1), Stefan Schönert (1), Christoph Wiesinger (1,2)
(1) Technische Universität München, (2) Max-Planck-Institut für Physik
[2] C. Wiesinger et al., Eur. Phys. J. C (2018) 78:597
[1] L. Pandola et al., Nucl. Instr. Methods A 570 (2007) 149
With passive and active measures the muon-induced background for LEGEND-1000 at LNGS is <10-6 cts/keV/kg/yr with <9% dead-time loss. With this, it contributes <10% to the total background goal.
- prompt interactions of shower constituents discriminated with >99% [0]
- delayed decays of in-situ produced 77(m)Ge are dominant [1,2]
Features in production and decay allow for additional reduction by
1. reducing the neturon flux at the Ge detectors
2. delayed coincidence rejection by 77mGe production tagging.
* standard background rejection are applied which strongly supresses 77Ge
- validated against indipendent frameworks [2,4] which are consistent with Gerda data
e.g. PE, PMMA or 5% borated PE
- energy deposition from neutron capture on Ge (gammas and recoil) and other shower particles
- delayed capture of sibling neutrons on Ar and/or on Gd in water.
77(m)Ge is dominantly produced by capture of high energy neutrons prompt (<10μs) after muon showers with high neutron multiplicity. Short lifetime of 77mGe allows to correlate production and decay.
(77mGe -> 77Ge) with 160keV-Gamma emission. Vetoing 11h individual detectors after tagging could further reduce 77Ge background.
